00:06:48,300 --> 00:06:49,400
OPEN HOUSE TODAY

142
00:06:50,200 --> 00:06:52,200
Detectives Jeffries, Rush.

143
00:06:53,400 --> 00:06:56,200
You were one of Tupperware's
top sellers back in '64 ?

144
00:06:56,201 --> 00:06:56,701
Yes.

145
00:06:56,800 --> 00:06:58,500
But I don't
sell it anymore.

146
00:06:58,500 --> 00:07:00,900
Wondering if you remember
Miriam Forrester ?

147
00:07:00,900 --> 00:07:02,800
I understand the two
of you were friends.

148
00:07:03,200 --> 00:07:06,700
Wow. Haven't heard that name
in a long time.

149
00:07:06,800 --> 00:07:07,700
Your Tupperware parties

150
00:07:07,700 --> 00:07:09,600
ever take you to Mississippi ?

151
00:07:10,400 --> 00:07:11,500
Lord, no.

152
00:07:11,700 --> 00:07:12,400
You have any idea

153
00:07:12,400 --> 00:07:14,700
what that kind of humidity
does to your hair ?

154
00:07:15,700 --> 00:07:18,600
Place was the epicenter
of civil rights action.

155
00:07:18,700 --> 00:07:20,700
Know if Miriam got involved ?

156
00:07:20,700 --> 00:07:22,800
What makes you think Miriam
was ever in Mississippi ?

157
00:07:22,800 --> 00:07:25,400
Well, this was found
in her overnight bag.

158
00:07:25,500 --> 00:07:28,000
It was sent from
Hazelton, Mississippi.

159
00:07:30,000 --> 00:07:31,600
This mean something to you ?

160
00:07:35,300 --> 00:07:37,300
The Tupperware gals
were all about

161
00:07:38,600 --> 00:07:41,800
getting a new sofa
or some fancy kitchen appliance.

162
00:07:41,900 --> 00:07:42,600
But Miriam ?

163
00:07:42,600 --> 00:07:44,600
Her thoughts ran deeper
than that.

164
00:07:46,000 --> 00:07:49,800
<i>"Walk On By"
by Dionne Warwick.</i>

165
00:07:51,100 --> 00:07:52,500
Lana make it home
all right ?

166
00:07:53,200 --> 00:07:55,500
Cute as a button,
that little thing.

167
00:07:58,600 --> 00:07:59,800
Miriam ?

168
00:08:05,800 --> 00:08:08,000
I know it's not polite
conversation,

169
00:08:08,500 --> 00:08:10,500
but have you seen
what's going on down there ?

170
00:08:14,200 --> 00:08:16,100
It's awful.

171
00:08:21,200 --> 00:08:23,200
Are you all right, Miriam ?

172
00:08:26,900 --> 00:08:27,700
Harold's never home.

173
00:08:27,700 --> 00:08:29,900
Even when he is,
we barely talk.

174
00:08:31,200 --> 00:08:34,000
I'm grateful to you for showing
me Tupperware; I really am.

175
00:08:34,000 --> 00:08:35,600
It's just sometimes...

176
00:08:36,200 --> 00:08:38,800
- What, dear ?
- Do you ever wonder

177
00:08:38,800 --> 00:08:40,300
if this is all there is ?

178
00:08:46,500 --> 00:08:49,200
She was what you would call
a "sensitive soul."

179
00:08:50,100 --> 00:08:52,200
Miriam didn't know how to drive.

180
00:08:52,400 --> 00:08:53,600
If she went to Mississippi,

181
00:08:53,600 --> 00:08:55,400
she would have needed someone
to take her.

182
00:08:55,400 --> 00:08:56,100
Well, if she did,

183
00:08:56,100 --> 00:08:57,600
it wasn't with me.

184
00:08:58,000 --> 00:08:59,000
I'm sorry.

185
00:08:59,000 --> 00:09:01,500
My open house
starts in five minutes.

186
00:09:11,200 --> 00:09:13,200
Hey, look who's back.

187
00:09:13,200 --> 00:09:15,900
Hmm, fit some shopping
into your busy day.

188
00:09:16,300 --> 00:09:17,400
Taking the Tupperware

189
00:09:17,400 --> 00:09:20,800
- research pretty serious, Nick.
- You wanted names.

190
00:09:21,100 --> 00:09:22,700
I got you names.

191
00:09:22,900 --> 00:09:24,300
Didn't come cheap,
did it?

192
00:09:24,600 --> 00:09:26,400
Another Tupperware lady
waiting for you.

193
00:09:26,800 --> 00:09:28,200
Name's Debra Nelson.

194
00:09:30,300 --> 00:09:31,400
No way.

195
00:09:31,900 --> 00:09:33,000
You take her.

196
00:09:33,000 --> 00:09:34,700
I'm done with these sharks.

197
00:09:39,400 --> 00:09:41,700
Been talking to some people
in Tupperware, Debra.

198
00:09:41,800 --> 00:09:44,200
You made the list
of high sellers in '64.

199
00:09:44,200 --> 00:09:46,400
Tupperware was
very popular back then.

200
00:09:46,400 --> 00:09:47,300
It still is today.

201
00:09:47,300 --> 00:09:49,000
Right. See, then
we looked you up.

202
00:09:49,000 --> 00:09:52,300
Got a string of arrests
in the '60s and '70s.

203
00:09:52,500 --> 00:09:54,700
Disorderly conduct,
civil disobedience...

204
00:09:54,700 --> 00:09:56,500
I'm proud of that record,

205
00:09:56,600 --> 00:09:58,400
protesting for our civil rights.

206
00:09:58,400 --> 00:09:59,800
And for that, I thank you.

207
00:10:00,200 --> 00:10:02,600
But in between protesting,

208
00:10:02,900 --> 00:10:04,600
you're selling
Tupperware.

209
00:10:05,200 --> 00:10:06,500
What am I missing here ?

210
00:10:07,700 --> 00:10:09,500
Tupperware was just a cover.

211
00:10:10,800 --> 00:10:13,600
Cover for what, exactly?

212
00:10:14,100 --> 00:10:15,700
Wednesday's Women.

213
00:10:16,100 --> 00:10:18,200
Housewives who
went to Mississippi.

214
00:10:18,400 --> 00:10:20,000
Traveled on Tuesday,

215
00:10:20,100 --> 00:10:21,500
arrived on Wednesday,

216
00:10:21,800 --> 00:10:22,900
back by the weekend.

217
00:10:22,900 --> 00:10:25,200
Black and white women ?
Together ?

218
00:10:25,200 --> 00:10:27,700
We brought supplies
to the Freedom Schools.

219
00:10:27,800 --> 00:10:29,500
Tried to help educate
black children

220
00:10:29,500 --> 00:10:32,100
who were being ignored
by the powers-that-be.

221
00:10:32,900 --> 00:10:35,700
You know anyone in Mississippi
who might've given

222
00:10:35,700 --> 00:10:37,300
this threat letter
to Miriam ?

223
00:10:38,800 --> 00:10:40,000
I stayed in Philly.

224
00:10:40,400 --> 00:10:42,600
Made arrangements
for the girls who were traveling.

225
00:10:42,600 --> 00:10:44,500
Must've been dangerous work
for them.

226
00:10:44,700 --> 00:10:48,500
It was my job to make them
aware of just how dangerous.

227
00:10:49,900 --> 00:10:52,600
When in public, you have
to wear your white gloves.

228
00:10:52,600 --> 00:10:53,900
We've got to
look the part,

229
00:10:53,900 --> 00:10:56,100
like genteel
Southern ladies.

230
00:10:56,300 --> 00:10:58,500
If anyone asks,
and they will,

231
00:10:58,900 --> 00:11:00,800
tell them you're there
to sell Tupperware.

232
00:11:00,800 --> 00:11:04,100
Even your hosts think
that's what you're there for.

233
00:11:04,400 --> 00:11:06,200
Most important,

234
00:11:06,300 --> 00:11:10,600
whites and coloreds
can't be seen together ever.

235
00:11:10,600 --> 00:11:12,400
And not just in Mississippi:

236
00:11:12,500 --> 00:11:14,400
any state below the Mason-Dixon.

237
00:11:14,400 --> 00:11:15,600
That's right, Ella.

238
00:11:15,600 --> 00:11:17,400
And don't discuss the locations

239
00:11:17,500 --> 00:11:20,600
of the Freedom Schools
with anyone,
not even each other.

240
00:11:20,600 --> 00:11:23,700
- Why ?
- Because the KKK is burning them down.

241
00:11:23,700 --> 00:11:25,200
- The schools?
- Three activists

242
00:11:25,200 --> 00:11:26,300
have gone missing
from a town

243
00:11:26,300 --> 00:11:27,700
near where we're going.

244
00:11:28,100 --> 00:11:29,300
College students.

245
00:11:29,500 --> 00:11:30,800
Two white, one black.

246
00:11:31,500 --> 00:11:34,200
Next group leaves
first Tuesday in August.

247
00:11:34,500 --> 00:11:36,100
Whoever wants to be in it,

248
00:11:36,400 --> 00:11:37,800
come get your gloves.

249
00:12:07,200 --> 00:12:09,100
Violet Golding was there ?

250
00:12:09,100 --> 00:12:11,400
She's the one who introduced
Miriam to the group.

251
00:12:11,800 --> 00:12:13,100
You still have that guestbook ?

252
00:12:13,100 --> 00:12:14,500
Sure, I could find it.

253
00:12:14,500 --> 00:12:16,300
So, Violet not only knew

254
00:12:16,300 --> 00:12:18,700
Miriam went to Mississippi,
she went with her.

255
00:12:19,200 --> 00:12:21,400
Violet, Miriam,

256
00:12:21,600 --> 00:12:23,900
Ella, and Belinda.

257
00:12:24,600 --> 00:12:26,000
They all went together.

258
00:12:33,600 --> 00:12:35,900
Violet lied.
Went to Mississippi, too.

259
00:12:35,900 --> 00:12:37,500
On her way in now.

260
00:12:37,700 --> 00:12:38,600
Can't wait to...

261
00:12:38,600 --> 00:12:39,900
hear her excuse.

